AHE-1,"Jackson, Lily (LEJackson47)","Jackson, Lily (LEJackson47)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Human Ecology,"Bell, Darci","Background: Artificial sweetener consumption has increased in recent years, and nutrition and medical professionals are beginning to question if there are any long-term health implications, especially with prolonged consumption patterns. Cardiovascular disease is a leading cause of death, and researchers are considering whether there is a potential correlation between artificial sweetener consumption and the risk of cardiovascular disease in adults. 

Purpose statement: The purpose of this literature review is to examine the possible connection between the consumption of artificial sweeteners and the prevalence of cardiovascular disease in adults through reviewing current, available literature. 

Results: Artificial sweeteners are potentially linked to neurological disorders, stroke, and metabolic risk factors. In addition, research has shown that those who consume a higher amount of artificial sweeteners are potentially at a heightened risk for developing cardiovascular disease in their lifetime.

Conclusions: Due to the non-experimental nature of the research articles within and the literature itself, causality cannot be determined at this time. However, the results of the articles referenced and the literature review set the foundation for future experimental research projects.

Implications: Individuals involved in all areas of public health should consider the potential impact of artificial sweetener consumption on the general adult population to guide their platforms for change, education, and the dissemination of nutrition information.",Literature based Review,Artificial Sweeteners and the Risk of Cardiovascular Disease in Adults,Yes,No,No,Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,AHE - Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,25
AHE-2,"Cruz, Jada (jcruz44)","Cruz, Jada (jcruz44)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Education and Human Sciences,Human Ecology,"Bell, Darci","Depression and anxiety are the leading mental health disorders in the world and increasing evidence supports that nutrition significantly influences the cause, severity and management of mental health conditions. The field of nutrition explores how diet patterns, inflammation potential and gut health impact mental health, specifically depression and anxiety. This literature review examines the relationship between nutrition and its effects on depression and anxiety in adults. Evidence from the studies that suggests improved dietary patterns, especially those that follow Mediterranean style practices, anti-inflammatory diet practices and probiotic intervention can reduce depression and anxiety symptoms.",Literature based Review,The Effects of Nutrition on Depression and Anxiety in Adults,No,No,No,Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,AHE - Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,33
AHE-3,"Riddick, Sydney (sriddick42)","Riddick, Sydney (sriddick42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Human Ecology,"Bell, Darci","Cardiovascular disease continues to affect millions of adults worldwide, and both research and real-world experience show that everyday food choices play a powerful role in shaping risk. The Mediterranean Diet, built around plant foods, healthy fats, and lean protein sources like fish, has consistently been recognized as a practical approach to supporting heart health. This literature review examined studies from the past decade to better understand how closely following this dietary pattern influences cardiovascular outcomes in adults.

Across clinical trials and cohort studies, the findings were clear. Greater adherence was associated with improvements in cholesterol, inflammation, and vascular function in the short term, while long-term adherence was linked to slower atherosclerosis progression and reduced risk of cardiovascular and overall mortality.

Overall, the evidence strongly supports the Mediterranean Diet as a realistic and effective strategy for improving heart health, while highlighting the need to better understand the real life factors that influence long-term adherence.",Literature based Review,Mediterranean Diet Adherence and Cardiovascular Disease Prevention in Adults,No,No,No,Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,AHE - Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,34
AHE-4,"Cicero, Lillian (lmcicero42)","Cicero, Lillian (lmcicero42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Human Ecology,"Bell, Darci","Background: About 26% of the female population is of reproductive age, with most women menstruating
from two to seven days each month. There is a known lack of information about menstruation. The topics
cycle syncing and menstrual phases have been gaining popularity on social media.
Methods: Articles were found for this literature review using the Tennessee Technological University Library
Eagle Search and PubMed. Search terms included menstrual cycle, menstrual phases, cycle phases,
nutritional intake, intake, nutritional biomarkers, energy, follicular, luteal, ovulation, menstrual, and appetite.
Articles were limited to those with focus on the menstrual phases and nutrition. Articles were excluded if
they were published earlier than 2015.
Results: The results found for energy intake, macronutrient intake, and micronutrient intake were mixed.
Most results indicated the luteal phase increased cravings and appetite compared to the follicular phase.
Ovulation increased exploratory food behaviors. The biomarkers ferritin, zinc, and magnesium declined from
the follicular to the luteal phase. The menstrual phase showed an increased intake of vitamin C, B vitamins,
fiber, potassium, magnesium, and zinc. The biomarkers total cholesterol, low-density lipoprotein cholesterol,
and cholesterol ratios were lower in the luteal phase.
Conclusions: The results are mixed and contradictory regarding intake. There were significant changes
observed in food cravings, taste preferences, and biomarkers across the menstrual cycle. Health
professionals need to consider these changes in order to provide accurate assessments and appropriate
care.",Literature based Review,"Menstrual Cycle Phase, Dietary Intake, Food Behavior, and Nutritional Biomarkers in Menstruating Women Across the Globe",No,No,No,Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,AHE - Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,,,,N/A,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,50
AHE-5,"Mingle, Morgan (mgmingle42)","Mingle, Morgan (mgmingle42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Human Ecology,"Bell, Darci","Background: Food insecurity is a public health concern that has been impacting families within the United States for decades. 
Objective/Purpose Statement: This literature review aims to identify patterns and observations that indicate a connection between food insecurity and the consumption of ultra-processed foods within families in the United States.
Results: Adults with very low food security consume a higher percentage of calories from ultra-processed foods at 55.7% as opposed to those with very high food security counterparts at 52.6%. Ultra-processed foods are typically more affordable and shelf-stable, making them an essential resource for combating food insecurity. The possible relationship between ultra-processed food consumption and food insecurity can be highlighted by SNAP participants presenting with poorer diet quality and inadequate cardiometabolic health outcomes.4
Conclusions: Increased risk factors for food insecurity, nutrition concerns related to the consumption of ultra-processed foods, the classification of ultra-processed foods, the impact of food insecurity and ultra-processed food consumption on families, and the increased risk factors for adverse health outcomes were found to be impacted by increased ultra-processed food intake. 
Implications: These findings provide justification for further research and the need for government program reform to provide equitable care and support access to healthy foods for Families in the United States. 
",Literature based Review,The Potential Relationship between Ultra-Processed Food Consumption and Food Insecurity,Yes,No,No,Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,AHE - Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,51
AHE-6,"Pennington, Brandy (bpenningt42)","Pennington, Brandy (bpenningt42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Human Ecology,"Bell, Darci","Background: Vitamin D deficiency is common in women diagnosed with poly cystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS). PCOS is characterized by anovulation, irregular menstruation, amenorrhea, hirsutism, and infertility. There is a growing body of evidence on vitamin D3 and its role in the regulation of hormone, symptoms, and metabolic risk factors associated with PCOS.
Objective/Purpose Statement: The aim of this study was to determine the potential relationship between vitamin D3 and PCOS diagnosis in women.
Results: Deficient vitamin D levels can exacerbate symptoms of PCOS. The literature provides a strong, convincing argument that there is a significant relationship between vitamin D deficiency and hormonal levels evidenced by an increase in androgen hormones, LH, and FSH levels in PCOS patients. There is also a significant relationship between vitamin D deficiency and metabolic factors as evidenced by the exacerbation of insulin resistance, insulin, and fasting glucose levels. Upon supplementation, the same hormonal levels and metabolic factors saw improvement as seen in studies that conducted 8–12-week trials.
Conclusions: Vitamin D has a positive relationship with PCOS diagnosis. Supplementation of this vitamin has the ability to better manage symptoms through regulating hormonal levels and decreasing metabolic factors associated with PCOS diagnosis like insulin resistance and high glucose levels. 
Implications: Current research shows that vitamin D supplementation, for patients with a deficiency, would be a valuable therapy to aid alongside the current management plan to help manage PCOS symptoms. By supplementing vitamin D, PCOS patients can improve insulin resistance, support reproductive health, manage hyperandrogenism, reduce inflammation, and lower their risk for other diseases like type 2 diabetes and cardiovascular disease.
",Literature based Review,The Potential Relationship Between Vitamin D3 and PCOS Diagnosis in Women,Yes,No,No,Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,AHE - Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,80
AHE-7,"Nutt, Gabrielle (ganutt42)","Nutt, Gabrielle (ganutt42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Human Ecology,"Bell, Darci","Background: Overweight and obesity rates during childhood are increasing in low-income and high-income nations around the world. A potential factor in these rising rates could be due to overnutrition, which is malnutrition from an overconsumption of specific nutrients that could lead to an increase in body weight. Unfortunately, a high body weight status during childhood can cause the development of poor health outcomes during childhood and adulthood.
Objective/Purpose Statement: Research was conducted to evaluate childhood (2-19 years old) overnutrition health outcomes. 
Results: Findings from research illustrated how nutritional intake and a high weight status can impact the anatomical structure and metabolic functioning of the cardiovascular system during childhood and adulthood. Additionally, findings showed trends in non-alcoholic fatty liver disease in children with a high weight status and poor liver health outcomes in adulthood. Lastly, research exhibited increasing rates of type 2 diabetes in children with a high weight status. Research also showed that a high weight status during childhood had higher rates of type 2 diabetes and/ or pancreatic cancer in adulthood.
Conclusions: Conclusions from the research conducted correlated poor cardiovascular, liver, and endocrine health outcomes with dietary intake and high weight status during childhood.
Implications: Findings in the review may provide a foundation for general knowledge on this topic, policy change, and intervention formation. ",Literature based Review,Health Outcomes of Childhood Overnutrition,Yes,No,No,Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,AHE - Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,,,,N/A,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,99
AHE-8,"Norman, Jadyn (jcnorman42)","Norman, Jadyn (jcnorman42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Human Ecology,"Bell, Darci","Carbohydrates have been heavily studied in the field of athletes and nutrition plans, but there has not been much research conducted on electrolytes even though they play a crucial role in homeostasis, contractions, and sweat loss during extended periods of exercise. It is important to determine correlations as ultra-racers are at risk experiencing exercise-associated hyponatremia and dehydration. The purpose of this literature review is to review the possible correlation between electrolytes and performance in endurance athletes using research from the past 15 years. The results of this literature review showed improved fatigue with electrolyte supplementation, although there were inconsistent results on speed, race finish times, and cardiovascular drift, serum electrolyte stability, and improved endurance. To conclude this paper, there were mixed results, and the evidence cited does not establish a cause-and-effect relationship between electrolyte supplementation and improved performance. On the contrary, sodium supplementation in some studies showed improved interventions when individualized. Implications of this paper show that future research should include larger sample sizes with a variety of participants to encompass a broader biological makeup of the population. It is essential to continue focusing on hydration status in practice to prevent illnesses related to exercise.",Literature based Review,The Role of electrolytes on Performance in Endurance Athletes,Yes,No,No,Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,AHE - Dean of Ag & Human Ecology,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,116
AHE-9,"Putman, Riley (rsputman42)","Putman, Riley (rsputman42);Tulsi, Ahmad (aatulsi42);Fuller, Nickolas (nrfuller42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Zhang, Jinfa","Fusarium wilt (FW) caused by Fusarium oxysporum f. sp. vasinfectum (FOV) is a soil-borne fungal disease that affects cotton plants across the Cotton Belt. Developing and growing FW-resistant cultivars is the most cost-effective method for managing FW. Accurate and efficient disease detection is essential for large-scale disease resistance identification. A total of 329 cotton stem segments cut from the soil level of FOV- infested field plots were visually sorted into 6 categories of vascular discoloration (VD), ranging from 0 with no VD, to 5 with >75% VD. This study scanned and annotated cotton stems to automate computer-based predictions. Using machine learning, pre-trained models can be specialized to detect VD and other important visual symptoms of the disease. This study initially screened 8 pre-trained models before proceeding with the 3 best predictors of VD. After training on this novel dataset, the best performing model was based on the pre-trained Feature Pyramid Network (FPN) model which is capable of predicting VD with >99% accuracy. This 2025 study details the positive correlation between VD% by ground truth and VD% by prediction, suggesting that machine learning is a powerful tool that should be further developed for disease resistance identification.",Research Project,Evaluation of Cotton for Resistance to Fusarium Wilt Race 4 Using Machine Learning,Yes,No,Yes,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,We used transfer learning to specialize pre-trained models for disease recognition predictions in cotton.,,,"Dr. Abdul Momin
Tennessee Technological University

Dr. Terry Wheeler
Texas A&M ArgiLife Research",,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,94
AHE-10,"Jarosz, Jacqueline (jjarosz42)","Jarosz, Jacqueline (jjarosz42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Bowhay, Ciana","This project presents a literature-based review of equine cloning by Somatic Cell Nuclear Transfer (SCNT), an advanced assisted reproductive technology used to produce a genetically identical copy of an existing horse. Since the birth of the first cloned horse, Prometea, in 2003, SCNT has evolved into a limited commercial and conservation tool. This review synthesizes peer reviewed veterinary literature, industry reports, and academic research to examine the cloning process, historical development, efficiency limitations, postnatal health outcomes, and ethical considerations. 

Despite technical progress, equine cloning remains highly inefficient, with success rates often below 3%, and ranging from 11% to as little as 0.7%. Significant variability in reported outcomes across studies highlights a need for standardized protocol and system of measurement for cloning success across the industry. In addition to embryonic failure, SCNT produces high rates of fetal and neonatal loss. Common challenges include abnormal placental development and Cloned Offspring Syndrome, which contributes to neonatal complications such as limb deformity, umbilical abnormalities, and increased risk of sepsis. While SCNT offers unique benefits including preservation of elite genetics, reproduction of infertile geldings, and conservation applications, significant welfare concerns remain. Continued research, improved efficiency, standardized methodologies, and greater transparency are essential before broader adoption of this technique can be ethically justified.",Literature based Review,A Comprehensive Review of Equine Reproductive Technologies: Cloning by Somatic Cell Nuclear Transfer,Yes,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,127
AHE-11,"Mullis, Raven (rsmullis42)","Mullis, Raven (rsmullis42);Osborne, Emma (egosborne42);Williams, Cole (crwilliams46);DiMisa, Jackson (jdimisa42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Nattrass, Michael","Phosphorus is an essential plant nutrient but can contribute to environmental degradation when lost through leaching into water systems. This study investigated how soil texture and pH influence phosphorus leaching in agricultural soils. Silt loam and sandy loam soils were treated with amendments to alter pH and were subjected to controlled water applications over a three-day period. Leachate samples were collected and analyzed for phosphorus concentration. Results indicated that silt loam soils exhibited greater phosphorus leaching compared to sandy loam soils. Additionally, soil pH played a role in phosphorus mobility, with near-neutral conditions helping to limit nutrient loss. These findings suggest that both soil texture and pH management are important factors in reducing phosphorus leaching and improving nutrient retention in agricultural systems.",Research Project,Influence of Soil Texture and pH on Phosphorus Leaching in Agricultural Soils,Yes,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,138
AHE-12,"Tulsi, Ahmad (aatulsi42)","Tulsi, Ahmad (aatulsi42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Environmental Studies,"Momin, Abdul","Rapid evaluation of soybean sample cleanliness during harvest is still largely based on visual inspection and manual sieving, which can be subjective and inconsistent for repeated field use. This study developed a smartphone-assisted sieving platform for on-farm soybean pre-screening by integrating physical fractionation, object detection, and Android deployment. The platform was designed as a three-region system to separate material other than grain (MOG), whole soybeans, and split/debris fractions into distinct areas. Platform evaluation under three mixture conditions showed that no whole soybeans entered Area 3 and no pod or stalk material reached Area 3 across all runs, indicating successful bulk separation. The main limitations were husk carryover into Area 2, localized stacking of soybeans in the imaging region, and soybean retention in the brush/bridge area under higher residue loading.

A total of 50 sieving events were used for image acquisition, and AprilTag-based localization enabled automatic ROI extraction and area-specific preprocessing. The final dataset comprised 600 images annotated into four classes: soybean, split, MOG, and MOG_husk. An ablation study of 41 experiments identified YOLO11l as the best research model, achieving mAP50 of 0.945 and mAP50-95 of 0.778, while YOLO11n ONNX FP16 was selected for Android deployment. The developed application performed fully on-device inference and completed post-capture analysis in approximately 1–2 s, demonstrating the feasibility of practical field-level soybean sample screening.",Research Project,"DEVELOPMENT OF A THREE-STAGE SIEVING PLATFORM AND YOLO-BASED ANDROID APPLICATION FOR SOYBEAN, SPLIT, AND MATERIAL OTHER THAN GRAIN DETECTION",No,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,143
AHE-13,"Cutshall, Ella (ecutshall42)","Cutshall, Ella (ecutshall42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Duncan, Dennis","This research focuses on how mental health directly affects a person’s ability to be food secure. The research has a specific focus on how mental health impacts food insecurity in college students. The inability to have access to nutritious, affordable, and sufficient food that provides adequate dietary demands in a person’s lifestyle is defined as food insecurity. Often people view food insecurity harshly without any understanding of the factors that dictate whether a person is food insecure or not. Specifically in college students, there is a wide range of backgrounds socially and economically that dictate the ability to be food secure. A survey was conducted from a pool of students who currently attend Tennessee Technological University to understand the correlation between mental health affects food insecurity, specifically topics such as anxiety, depression, and panic attacks. 

Keywords: Food insecurity, anxiety, depression, social inequalities, panic attacks, college student, socioeconomic status. 
",Research Project,Food Insecurity: The Psychological Barriers in College Students,Yes,Human Subjects,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,144
AHE-14,"Mullis, Raven (rsmullis42)","Mullis, Raven (rsmullis42);Mulderink, Jon (jpmulderin42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Duncan, Dennis","This study examines the use of crossbreeding between dairy and beef cattle in Scottish livestock production systems, based on observations made during a visit to Scotland's Rural College in Dumfries. Unlike traditional practices in the United States, where dairy and beef production are often separated, Scottish farmers commonly crossbreed dairy cows with beef sires to improve the value and efficiency of meat production. This approach allows for better utilization of dairy calves while enhancing carcass quality compared to pure dairy animals. Observational comparisons suggest that this system increases overall farm efficiency and may contribute to more sustainable livestock production. The findings highlight key differences between Scottish and U.S. cattle systems and suggest that integrating crossbreeding strategies could provide economic and production benefits in American agriculture.",Research Project,Crossbreeding Dairy and Beef Cattle: An Observational Study of Scottish Livestock Production System,Yes,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,150
AHE-15,"Broski, Emma (egbroski42)","Broski, Emma (egbroski42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Idowu, Modoluwamu","This study will evaluate the effects of a probiotic supplement containing Enterococcus and Lactobacillus on rumen microbial activity and digestion across different feed types. Rumen fermentation plays a critical role in nutrient utilization, directly influencing growth performance and health in cattle. Therefore, strategies that enhance rumen function, such as probiotic supplementation, may improve feed efficiency. An in vitro fermentation system will be used to assess the impact of probiotic supplementation on two feed substrates: hay, and a total mixed ration (TMR). Fresh rumen fluid will be collected from an Angus beef steer using an orally administered stomach tube connected to a vacuum pump. The rumen fluid will then be incubated with each feed type under probiotic-supplemented and control conditions for 48 hours at 39°C in a water bath. Key fermentation parameters, including gas production, pH, microbial activity, and dry matter digestibility, will be measured to evaluate digestive efficiency and microbial responses. Data will be analyzed using a two-way ANOVA to determine the significance (p ≤ 0.05) of the effects of probiotic supplementation, feed type, and their interaction. We expect that probiotic supplementation would enhance microbial activity, stabilize ruminal pH, and improve digestibility compared to the control. Findings from this study will provide insight into the functional role of probiotics in ruminant nutrition and their potential to improve feed efficiency. Given that feed costs account for approximately 50-60% of livestock production costs, optimizing nutrient utilization through probiotic supplementation may offer a practical and sustainable strategy for improving profitability. ",Research Project,In Vitro Rumen Fermentation to Evaluate Effects of Probiotics on Digestion and Microbial Activity Using Different Feed Types ,Yes,Animal Subjects,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,2526005,2026,155
AHE-16,"Buie, Morgan (mmbuie42)","Buie, Morgan (mmbuie42);Johns, Sophia (sljohns42);Dempsey, Laurel (ladempsey42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Idowu, Modoluwamu","Which Food Categories Experienced the Highest Inflation?
Morgan Buie, Sophia Johns, Laurel Dempsey, Dr. Lianqun Sun 
School Of Agriculture 
Abstract 
Our research project analyzes which food categories experienced the highest inflation in comparison. Using public data from the U.S Bureau of Labor Statistics, our study compares price changes across common food categories, including eggs, dairy, meats, and produce. The dataset is obtained from the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics and organized into a spreadsheet format. Data Preparation includes category comparison, calculation of inflation by category, selection of a consistent timeframe, and computation of changes using index values. Incomplete data points will be excluded if necessary. Data cleaning involves removing unnecessary variables and standardizing category names. The analysis focuses on comparing inflation rates across categories, using percentage changes. Bar chart and other charts will be used to visually present the differences across the categories to identify which food categories experienced the largest price increase. Figure 1 shows that nonalcoholic beverages and cereals experienced the highest inflation rates, while dairy products showed minimal or slightly negative price change. Understanding which food categories experienced the highest inflation is important for both the economy and agribusiness. Steep increases in prices can influence consumer behavior, agricultural production decisions, and overall food security.   
Figure 1. 12 Month Percentage Change, Consumer Price Index, selected categories, from U.S. BLS, 2026)
",Research Project,"""Which Food Categories Experienced the Highest Inflation?""",No,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,156
AHE-17,"Borum, Gauge (grborum42)","Borum, Gauge (grborum42);Rawdon, Caleb (chrawdon42);Blankenship, William (wablankens42);Mainord, Grant (gmainord42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Momin, Abdul","The Digital Inventory Location Tool (DILT) is a capstone design project that develops a spatially enabled inventory management system for nursery operations, with a focus on balled-and-burlapped (B&B) plant inventory. Traditional inventory tracking in nurseries often relies on manual searches and operator memory, leading to inefficiencies and increased labor time. This project aims to design, develop, and evaluate a digital, map-based tool that enables users to locate plant inventory by species, size, and planting year using a structured grid or section-based spatial framework. The system integrates QGIS, Google Maps, and web-based technologies to create a mobile-friendly interface accessible from internet-enabled devices. Development includes field-based testing, time data collection, and validation at a working nursery to assess usability and performance. The expected outcome is a functional prototype that demonstrates reduced search time, improved inventory accuracy, and enhanced operational efficiency, with potential for broader application across agricultural and landscaping industries.",Research Project,Digital Inventory Location Tool (DILT): A Spatially Enabled System for Efficient Nursery Inventory Management,Yes,No,Yes,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,"In order to develop DILT for the web, our team has began to use a website to help build the tool. This website uses AI to better organize the idea that lies within our mind for the tool, as we begin to give more in depth prompts on what we are looking for it offers solutions for the looks and uses of certain parts of the tool. This is to help us refine it in ways that we had previously overlooked, it is not building DILT completely for us, it is simply giving the team a baseline to continue to build and develop from.",,,"Blankenship Farms & Nursery, Jerry Blankenship (Owner/Operator)",,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,168
AHE-18,"York, Briley (btyork42)","York, Briley (btyork42);Jenkins, Avery (arjenkins43);Utley, Caeson (cbutley42);Elgaithie, Abdullah (aselgaithi42);Baier, James",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Momin, Abdul","ROTMV is a capstone design project aimed at improving safety and operational efficiency in mowing hazardous terrains such as steep slopes and ditches. Conventional man-operated mowers in these environments present significant risks, including rollover incidents and operator injury. This project focuses on the design, construction, and evaluation of a remotely controlled turf maintenance system capable of operating in areas where traditional equipment is unsafe. The system integrates a 17.5 HP engine, dual 12-volt battery configurations, electric drive wheels, and a 42-inch mower deck within a custom steel frame. Most components have been procured, and system layout and assembly are currently in progress. A key design challenge involves optimizing the deck-lifting mechanism to minimize structural stress and ensure reliable operation. Future work will include system integration, controlled testing, and performance evaluation under field conditions.",Research Project,Remote-Operated Turf Maintenance Vehicle (ROTMV),No,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,169
AHE-19,"Holloway, Davie (dmholloway42)","Holloway, Davie (dmholloway42);Bowhay, Ciana",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Bowhay, Ciana","As residential development continues to expand into natural landscapes, existing ecosystems are heavily altered by land clearing, construction, and landscaping. Developers and homeowners tend to choose non-native, ornamental varieties to fit aesthetic preferences. Non-native plants offer limited benefit to local wildlife, especially birds and insects that have evolved alongside and rely on native plant species to survive. Habitat loss and the lack of host plants contribute to a decline in biodiversity and negatively affect insect populations. Incorporating native species in residential landscapes can support ecosystem health and potentially mitigate some of the impacts of development. Despite these benefits, many homeowners lack awareness of the native plants in their region and their ecological importance. Additionally, native plants are often less available in commercial nurseries than non-native species, further limiting their adoption. This study surveys Middle Tennessee homeowners to assess their current knowledge and attitudes toward native plants and to evaluate whether increased awareness of their ecological benefits influences their willingness to purchase and incorporate native plants into residential landscapes. The survey uses a pre-post design. Participants respond to baseline questions, view a brief research-based infographic, and then complete post-exposure questions. Key measures are repeated to assess changes in knowledge, attitudes, and willingness to purchase native plants. Findings from this study will provide insight into the effectiveness of simple educational tools in promoting public acceptance of native plants in residential landscaping and supporting local ecosystem health. 
",Research Project,The Impact of an Educational Infographic on Homeowner Knowledge and Purchase Intentions for Native Plants in Middle Tennessee,Yes,Human Subjects,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,3067,,2026,172
AHE-20,"Fuller, Nickolas (nrfuller42)","Fuller, Nickolas (nrfuller42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Interdisciplinary Studies,Environmental Studies,"Sun, Lianqun","This project has conducted surveys of local retailers, both in direct-to-consumer farmer’s market settings and small local retail stores in the rural, agricultural Upper Cumberland region of central Tennessee. These surveys were utilized in a robust economic analysis of local food systems in the Upper Cumberland region. The top selling products at farmer's markets are vegetables, fruits, and baked goods. Eighty-nine percent of participants reported selling direct-to-consumer at farmers’ markets only once or twice a week. Seventy-seven percent of farmers reported earning less than $500 per market day. Vegetables and fruits surpassed all other categories of foods being sold at stores. Of the stores that sell local foods, most stores sold more than 50% of their products originating from local sources. From the surveys collected from farmers selling at farmers markets, an IMPLAN input-output economic analysis estimated a total economic output of farmers markets between $2,996,878.15 and $7,977,337.19 for the Upper Cumberland Region of Tennessee. Results will provide insight into the economic contribution of local food systems, identify key marketing and production challenges faced by farmers and retailers, and highlight opportunities to strengthen linkages between producers, retailers, and consumers.",Research Project,A Survey Report and Economic Impact Analysis of Locally Produced Agricultural Products in the Upper Cumberland Region of Tennessee,Yes,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,Joshua Reed (Tennessee Technological University),,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,194
AHE-21,"Hair, Jacob (jhair42)","Hair, Jacob (jhair42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Shrestha, Surya","Neopestalotiopsis spp. are emerging fungal pathogens of strawberry (Fragaria × ananassa), causing fruit rot and significant yield losses. Understanding host-pathogen interactions at the biochemical level is critical for improving disease management strategies. This study investigates physiological responses of strawberry fruits to Neopestalotiopsis infection by monitoring soluble sugar content and oxalic acid concentration across the disease progression curve. Plant tissues and fruits were collected from multiple commercial farms across Tennessee, capturing natural variation in disease incidence and environmental conditions. Samples were categorized according to stages of infection, from early symptom development to advanced decay. Soluble sugar measurements were used to evaluate alterations in primary metabolism, while oxalic acid levels were quantified due to their role in fungal pathogenicity. Preliminary results indicate dynamic metabolic shifts: early infection stages exhibit altered sugar distribution, suggesting disruption of normal carbohydrate metabolism, while oxalic acid concentrations increase progressively, potentially facilitating tissue maceration and pathogen establishment. These findings provide insight into the biochemical processes underlying disease progression and identify sugar and oxalic acid as potential biomarkers of infection severity. By combining field-collected samples with biochemical analyses, this study enhances understanding of Neopestalotiopsis-strawberry interactions under real-world conditions. The results have implications for early detection, crop management, and postharvest quality preservation, offering a foundation for strategies to mitigate losses caused by this emerging pathogen in Tennessee strawberry production.",Research Project,Changes in Fragaria × Ananassa Plant Chemistry in Relation to Degree of Neopestalotiopsis spp. Infection ,No,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,203
AHE-22,"Ledbetter, Shaela (saledbette42)","Ledbetter, Shaela (saledbette42);Begley, Lauren (lrbegley42);Miller, Megan (mlmiller43)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Sun, Lianqun","Agriculture is increasingly adopting new technologies to improve productivity, reduce costs, and manage resources more efficiently by using drones also known as unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs). Agricultural drones can monitor crop health, map fields, apply chemicals, and collect important data that help farmers make better management decisions. This study evaluates whether drone technology is a cost-effective investment for agricultural farms and how farm size affects profitability. A cost-benefit analysis approach is used to compare estimated costs for drone ownership and operation across farms of different sizes. Costs include purchase, maintenance, software, batteries, and labor, and are calculated on a per-acre basis. Economic benefits from using agricultural drones are provided through increased yields, reduced chemical use, and improved efficiency. The analysis shows that farm size plays a crucial role in determining the financial feasibility of drone adoption. According to the University of Missouri Extension, approximately 980 acres must be sprayed annually to break even, indicating that smaller farms may face greater challenges in adopting this technology. The findings suggest that drone technology can provide valuable economic and operational benefits for agricultural farms, but its cost-effectiveness strongly depends on farm size. While the initial investment may be challenging for smaller operations, drones still offer important advantages such as improved crop monitoring, reduced chemical waste, and faster decision-making.",Research Project,Economic Feasibility of Drone Adoption in Small and Large Farms,No,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,210
AHE-23,"Duncan, Dennis","Cartwright, Morgan (mcartwrig42);Miller, Maggie (memiller44)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Duncan, Dennis","Tennessee currently has over 220 high school FFA chapters and over 30,000 FFA members. FFA advisors train their students for career development events (CDE’s) and leadership development events (LDE’s). FFA advisors typically have a broad education, and sometimes lack the extensive knowledge and experience needed to prepare FFA members for specific CDE’s and LDE’s. Faculty and students in the School of Agriculture (SOA) at Tennessee Tech recognized the many challenges advisors face and developed training clinics structured according to state and national FFA CDE and LDE guidelines. University student clubs develop and organize the clinics - specific content and instruction provided by university faculty, volunteers, and experts with extensive FFA experience. The clinics provide FFA members with valuable experience that can prepare them for upcoming FFA events. Since 2012 over 4,000 FFA and 4-H members have attended clinics ranging from horse and livestock judging to floriculture, parliamentary procedure and veterinary science. In order to gauge the impact(s) of the aforementioned clinics, a study was conducted during multiple clinics and included 66 FFA advisors who have and/or had students who participated in FFA clinics at TN Tech. Results indicate that the majority of advisors strongly agree or somewhat agree that the clinics have supplemented their training and nearly 75% strongly agree or somewhat agree that the clinics have provided training they don’t have expertise in, and over half strongly agree that clinics have made their students more competitive.",Research Project,University Faculty and Students Helping High School Agriscience Teachers meet their Educational Goals,Yes,Human Subjects,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,2305,,2026,211
AHE-24,"Duncan, Dennis","Callicott, Sarah (sbcallicot42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,Lynette Harvey,"Food insecurity is a challenge that remains rooted even in the richest countries across the globe. Nations including Scotland and the United States attempt to tackle food insecurity amongst their citizens through various programs and community support. There are several key differences in how each nation approaches food insecurity and how effective they are in the fight to end hunger. This project explores the similarities and differences of food insecurity in the United States and Scotland as well as current measures to address food insecurity. The author pulled data from the Trussell Report: Ending Hunger Together (trussell.org.uk) – a national report that outlines the nature, scale, and drivers of hunger across Scotland. The most recent publication was released in September of 2025. Data shows that 15% of adults in Scotland face food insecurity that is often due to lower-than-average salaries, increasing food prices, mental and/or physical limitations, and rising housing costs. Additionally, one in seven households experienced food insecurity, as highlighted in the Trussell Report. These causes are not unique to Scotland or the United Kingdom as a whole. According to data released in 2024 by the United States Department of Agriculture’s Economic Research Service, nearly 14% of Americans households faced food insecurity. This represents nearly 34 million adults and approximately 7.3 million children in 2024. Lastly, families living in rural areas of both Scotland and the United States experienced food insecurity at higher levels than families living in urban sectors. ",Literature based Review,Food Insecurity in the 21st Century – The Tale of Two Countries,Yes,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,225
AHE-25,"Craig, Emily (egcraig42)","Craig, Emily (egcraig42);Pierce, Kenneth;Bowhay, Ciana;Idowu, Modoluwamu",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Bowhay, Ciana","Common mullein (Verbascum Thapsus L.) is a medicinal plant native to Europe, Asia, and Africa that was introduced to North America in the 18th century. It is commonly found on roadsides, pastures, and other disturbed environments due to its ability to thrive in nutrient-poor soils. Historically, mullein has been used by natives to treat pulmonary and integumentary ailments, and has also been found to treat minor auditory and musculoskeletal ailments, due to its anti-inflammatory properties. Mullein has many medicinal properties that make it attractive for cultivation for commercial and research purposes. 
To germinate, mullein seeds must go through a stratification or scarification process. Replicating these natural processes can be time consuming and inconsistent. The objective of this study is to evaluate the effectiveness of combining chemical and mechanical pre-treatments to accelerate germination. Seeds were subjected to five treatment groups, including combination of sandpaper scarification with gibberellic acid (GA₃), potassium nitrate (KNO₃), and indole-3-butyric acid/naphthaleneacetic acid (IBA/NAA). Each treatment consisted of three repetitions of 50 seeds, arranged in two rows of 25 that were placed on germination paper and rolled in a waxy paper. Seedlings were counted and measured to evaluate germination percentage and seedling growth. Findings from this study will provide insight into effective germination strategies for mullein, supporting more efficient cultivation and production practices. Improved propagation methods may encourage growers to produce mullein, making it more accessible to consumers and researchers for medicinal use.
",Research Project,Effects of Combining Mechanical and Chemical Pre-treatments on Germination of Common Mullein,Yes,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,226
AHE-26,"Dace, Nathaniel (njdace42)","Dace, Nathaniel (njdace42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Momin, Abdul","This project focuses on improving poultry welfare through the development of an automated gait tracking system using digital image processing. Gait scoring is a critical indicator of chicken health, as abnormalities in movement can signal lameness or injury, directly impacting both animal welfare and farm productivity. Traditional gait assessment methods are manual, subjective, and time-consuming, creating a need for more efficient and objective approaches. To address this, a camera-based system was installed in a poultry facility to continuously monitor chicken movement. High-definition overhead cameras captured video under varying lighting conditions, including low-light environments using infrared capabilities. The recorded footage was processed using image analysis software capable of detecting movement patterns and extracting gait-related metrics such as speed and stride characteristics. Preliminary results demonstrate that the system can successfully track poultry movement and identify behavioral patterns associated with mobility issues. This automated, non-invasive approach enables early detection of health concerns, supports data-driven farm management, and reduces labor requirements. Overall, the system shows strong potential as a scalable solution for enhancing poultry welfare and advancing precision agriculture practices.",Research Project,Gait Tracking Using Digital Image Processing For Enhancing Poultry Welfare,Yes,No,Yes,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,"AI was not a main contributor, rather an aid to enhance the camera based software. This project used machine learning to identify chicken gaits and track them through a image processing software (openCV). The cameras installed were Swann Security Surveillance - 5580.",,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,235
AHE-27,"Stalker, Emma (emstalker42)","Stalker, Emma (emstalker42)",Graduate Student | Doctoral,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Environmental Studies,"Momin, Abdul","Effectiveness of Household Water Filtration Pitchers in Removing Fiber Contaminants from Drinking Water 

Research and Creative Inquiry Symposium 

Emma Stalker & Dr. Abdul Momin 

The presence of microfibers in drinking water has become an increasing environmental and public health concern, particularly as everyday filtration systems are commonly relied upon to improve water quality. This study evaluated the effectiveness of four commercially available water filtration pitchers—Brita, PUR, Culligan, and Great Value—in removing hair fibers from tap water. Water samples were collected from a drinking fountain at Tennessee Technological University and experimentally spiked with hair fibers cut into approximately 0.5 cm segments to simulate fiber contamination. Equal volumes of the prepared water samples were passed through each filtration pitcher according to manufacturer's guidelines. The filtered water from each system was subsequently processed through a secondary laboratory filtration procedure to capture remaining particulate material. After filtration, samples were allowed to dry and were examined under a microscope to quantify the number of retained hair fibers and identify additional deposited particulates. Fiber counts were recorded to compare the relative filtration performance among the pitcher systems. This experimental design provides a controlled approach for assessing the ability of household water filtration devices to remove fiber contaminants from drinking water. The results contribute to a broader understanding of consumer-level filtration effectiveness and may inform future research on microfiber contamination and removal in domestic water treatment systems. ",Research Project,Effectiveness of Household Water Filtration Pitchers in Removing Fiber Contaminants from Drinking Water ,Yes,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,243
AHE-28,"France, Alina (alfrance42)","France, Alina (alfrance42);Wright, Kenya (klwright44);Hardin, Emma (enhardin43)",Undergraduate Student,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,Agriculture,"Sun, Lianqun",,Research Project,Dairy Price Trends & Inflation Adjustment,,No,No,School of Agriculture,AHE - School of Agriculture,,,,,,,AHE,College of Agriculture and Human Ecology,,,2026,254
