https://www.fws.gov/species-publication-action/designation-critical-habitat-physariaglobosa-shorts-bladderpod-7 
6.	Warren, C.R.  & Dreyer, E. (2006). Temperature response of photosynthesis and internal conductance to CO2: Results from two independent approaches | Journal of Experimental Botany | Oxford Academic. Retrieved October 15, 2024, from https://academic.oup.com/jxb/article/57/12/3057/445593 
 
How does the project extend your own present knowledge and contribute to your field of study? 
 	By accessing and analyzing the historical climate around P. globosa, I will be able to further develop valuable critical thinking and problem-solving skillsets. This project will also allow me to develop new analytical and large database organizational skills that I will able to utilize in future academic and professional projects. I will also gain valuable hands-on laboratory experience by participating in plant growth experiments. These particular experiences will allow me to better understand my field of study, cellular and molecular biology. During this project, I will produce a historical climate model based on the data collected to potentially display drastic climate changes that potentially impacted the local habits of P. globosa. This model could be used as a base for plant conservationists to use to create countermeasures against future climate changes. Those countermeasures could also help prevent the extinction of other plant species that are affected by climate change. 

Faculty Advisor: Dr. Hannah Kinmonth 
I worked with Dr. Kinmonth by meeting weekly to discuss project goals and appropriate work-life balance, seeking guidance on appropriate lab conduct and safety protocols, learning valuable analytical and organizational skills throughout the course of the project, and asking for assistance when/if navigating online databases proves challenging. I also anticipate needing guidance on an appropriate way to design and organize the climate change model as WorldClim, a software used to create climate models, seems to be a very complex. However, I am very excited and eager to learn from and work with Dr. Kinmonth throughout the course of this project if it is approved as I am optimistic that the outcome of this project will be an outstanding product.",Research Project,Physaria globosa Climate Data Collection,Yes,No,No,Biology,ASC - Biology,No use of A.I. on this project!,,,"Sarah Elliott, Graduate Student, Biology Department",,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,262
ASC-68,"Troth, Natalie (ngtroth42)","Hall, Joshua;Troth, Natalie (ngtroth42);McKinley, Jacey (jlmckinley43);Anderson, Kennedy (kanderson42);Skelton, Macie (mskelton42);Scruggs, Cindy (cscruggs42);Laffoon, Thomas (trlaffoon42);Zerr, Frankie (fjzerr42);Gordon, Alexander (agordon42);Deans, Quentin (qdeans42);Gaither, Logan (lwgaither42);Granados, Aileen (aegranados42);O'Neal, Alex",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Hall, Joshua",,Research Project,A preliminary analysis of salamander morphology at City Lake Natural Area,,Animal Subjects,No,Biology,ASC - Biology,,,,Grayson Hall (Devo Eco Lab),,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,2425004,2026,264
ASC-69,"Easterwood, Emmy (ebeasterwo42)","Easterwood, Emmy (ebeasterwo42);Wills, Zoe (zawills42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Hurt, Carla",,Research Project,Creation of a Taxonomic Database of Arthropods in Subterranean Environments in the Bridgestone/Firestone Wilderness Area of Tennessee,,No,No,Biology,ASC - Biology,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,265
ASC-70,"Marchese, Nora (nemarchese42)","Marchese, Nora (nemarchese42);Turner, Taylor (tjturner44)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Cohen, Bradley","Over the past two decades, the population of American Kestrels (Falco sparverius) has been in decline in Tennessee while the landscape has trended towards greater levels of development. This project aims to evaluate kestrel response to changing habitat from 2010-2024 and create an index of suitable habitat in the state. This will be evaluated in ArcGIS Pro using Cornell’s eBird reported sightings during the kestrel breeding season and reclassified National Land Cover Database (NLCD) data through a statistical analysis of which habitats the birds were reported in and generalized linear modeling. ",Research Project,American Kestrel Habitat Suitability in Tennessee,Yes,No,No,Biology,ASC - Biology,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,282
ASC-71,"Sporalsky, Kaiya (kjsporalsk42)","Sporalsky, Kaiya (kjsporalsk42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Kinmonth-Schultz, Hannah","Ornamental gardening and landscaping is a practice that has existed for centuries and persists today as a popular hobby amongst many demographics. It also serves as a common method to bring nature and beauty to both urban and rural areas. While gardening can be an excellent way to promote biodiversity, support pollinator populations, and prevent soil erosion, it can be a double-edged sword. Many of the most common ornamental plants found in numerous personal gardens, sold in nurseries and garden centers, and planted along roads and in neighborhoods are invasive plants. Such plants spread quickly and easily, and are prone to outcompeting native flora, in turn reducing biodiversity and having negative environmental consequences. The goal of this project is to provide the public with information on invasive plants that are commonly planted in gardens or used in landscaping, and encourage the use of alternatives that are native to Tennessee to promote local biodiversity and prevent further harm to Tennessee ecosystems.",Research Project,Designing Educational Resources for the Layman: Native and Invasive Plants,Yes,No,No,Biology,ASC - Biology,,,,"Katherine Pabody, Tennessee Tech University Graduate Student",,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,287
ASC-72,"Mount, Thomas (tjmount42)","Mount, Thomas (tjmount42);Dan, David",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Dan, David","Lanthanides are notoriously difficult to separate using conventional chemical methods because of their similar chemistries across the series. To remedy this, we aim to use a tunable Cu-based metal-organic framework (MOF) to separate lanthanides by atomic radius. This works by capturing the smaller of the two lanthanides within the MOF, allowing the larger one to flow around it with the MOF acting as a sieve. In order to test this, a MOF with copper nodes and terephthalic acid linkers was synthesized and then contacted with neodymium and samarium.  All MOFs were tested via powder X-ray diffraction to assess structural continuity, and experimental samples were tested using inductively coupled plasma optical emission spectroscopy (ICP-OES) to determine residual concentrations and assess efficiency. ",Research Project,Synthesis of a Cu-based metal-organic framework for lanthanide separation,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,78
ASC-73,"Casey, Elisabeth (egcasey42)","Casey, Elisabeth (egcasey42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Zhang, Hong","Iron species (ferric iron or Fe(III) and ferrous iron or Fe(II)) play a unique, important role in environmental chemistry. Fe(III) is known to spontaneously hydrolyze in an aqueous solution and the hydrolysis products then polymerize. The kinetics of the Fe(III) hydrolysis process was studied by following the change of [Fe(III)] species in aqueous solutions. This experiment was conducted using a set of aqueous FeCl3 solutions at a micro-molar level (100 μM); at time intervals desired, the Fe(III) in the solutions was reduced to Fe(II) by adding hydroxylamine (NH2OH•HCl) and then analyzed for [Fe(II)] spectrophotometrically. It was found that the [Fe(II)] decreased with time at various times of the addition of hydroxylamine to the FeCl3 solutions. We hypothesize that the Fe(III) species are polymerizing into hydroxylamine-irreducible forms of Fe(III) in the aqueous FeCl3 solutions before addition of hydroxylamine.",Research Project,A Study on Hydrolysis Behavior of Aqueous Ferric Iron (FeCl3) Using a Redox Analysis,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,None,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,95
ASC-74,"Knight, Lauren (lknight42)","Knight, Lauren (lknight42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Cojocaru, Oana","Solid-state thioridazine hydrochloride is associated with many challenges regarding its bioavailability, its formation of polymorphs, as well as severe side effects such as cardiac arrythmias. This pharmaceutical has the potential to overcome these challenges when converted into an ionic liquid (IL) and double salt ionic liquid (DSIL).In previous work, our group converted the thioridazine cation into a liquid-state drug by combining it with an anion and, in some cases, an additional cationic pharmaceutical with the potential to mitigate side effects. Sodium carboxylates and sodium docusate have the potential to serve as anion precursors, enabling the formation of liquid-state pharmaceuticals with dual functionality. Previously, these compounds were synthesized and characterized using spectroscopic techniques (NMR, IR) and thermal analysis (TGA, DSC).

To evaluate their therapeutic potential, transdermal delivery studies will be carried out using an automated continuous flow diffusion system (ILC07) equipped with a silicone membrane that mimics skin permeability. The mass of the compound that permeated the membrane will be quantified using UV-VIS spectroscopy, enabling comparison of transport efficiency between commercially available thioridazine hydrochloride and different liquid-state thioridazine formulations.",Research Project,Transdermal Delivery of Liquid-State Thioridazine Compounds,No,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,"Claire Rust, Tennessee Tech University, Department of Chemistry",,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,103
ASC-75,"Opoku Acheampong, Clement (copokuach42)","Opoku Acheampong, Clement (copokuach42);Tetteh, Michael (mttetteh42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Zhang, Hong","Mercury (Hg) contamination in freshwater ecosystems remains a persistent environmental and public health concern due to its toxicity, environmental persistence, and ability to bioaccumulate in aquatic organisms. Long-term environmental monitoring programs generate extensive datasets that can provide valuable insights into contamination patterns across time and space. However, these datasets are often underutilized for systematic analysis. The Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation (TDEC) has conducted statewide monitoring of Hg concentrations in fish collected from lakes across multiple counties. This open-access database provides an opportunity to apply data-mining approaches to identify spatial and temporal trends in Hg contamination and evaluate potential environmental risk indicators. 
In this study, Hg concentration records obtained from the TDEC fish tissue monitoring database were compiled and organized to examine patterns across lakes in TN. Statistical visualization and exploratory data analysis techniques were applied to evaluate the distribution and variability of mercury concentrations relative to the commonly referenced fish consumption advisory threshold of 0.3 mg/kg. Future work will focus on applying rational molecular peptide design, particularly cysteine-based sequences that selectively bind Hg²⁺ via sulfur coordination chemistry, as a potential strategy for removing Hg from lake systems that exceed the advisory limit.
",Research Project,Analyzing Fish Mercury (Hg) Trends and Patterns across Tennessee Lakes using the Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation (TDEC) Fish Hg Database,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,104
ASC-76,"Stone, Natalie (ngstone42)","Stone, Natalie (ngstone42);Boles, Jeffrey",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Boles, Jeffrey","An important aspect of science is work carried out under efficient and affordable conditions. The current standard when determining unknown protein concentrations with a dye is Coomassie Blue and although effective, it can be costly. My research is to discover a suitable protein dye that is effective and less costly than the Coomassie Blue. There are many compounds that are known to bind proteins and this also includes food colorings. For the reasons of cost and impact to the environment, I’ve chosen to focus on Yellow dye No. 5 (Tartrazine) and Tumeric (Curcumin). Several experiments are being conducted using these two dyes using Bovine Serum Albumin (BSA) as a standard protein. Varying concentrations of BSA are selected and incubated with the dye for varying time periods, followed by analysis by a UV/IS spectrophotometer in order to create standard curves. Each will be plotted and fit by linear regression and compared to the commercially available Coomassie Blue commonly used to produce such standard curves. If successful, I will be able to provide a more cost efficient dye that can do the same job of Coomassie Blue, if not better. 
",Research Project,Discovering Suitable Dyes for Protein Staining ,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,106
ASC-77,"Anderson, Emma (eganderson45)","Anderson, Emma (eganderson45);Cable, Bella (bjcable42);Bacon, Chance (cmbacon42);Curington, Spencer (sccuringto42);O'Neal, Alex",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Zhang, Hong","Iron (Fe) is ubiquitous. It has two main environmental species, (i) ferrous Fe (Fe(II)), soluble and mobile, and (ii) ferric Fe (Fe(III)), insoluble. Fe(II) can be oxidized to Fe(III) by oxygen (O2), while Fe(III) can be reduced to Fe(II). This redox cycling between Fe(III) and Fe(II) is important in soil and water chemistry. The environmental Fe(III)/Fe(II) redox occurs abiotically and also microbially. Previous research reported Fe(II) formation via microbial reduction of soil Fe(III) oxides, stimulated by sugar (glucose, a monosaccharide) in a laboratory setting; this was followed by oxidation of the Fe(II) back to Fe(III) to generate iridescent Fe(III) films floating on water, exhibiting a unique environmental phenomenon of microbially mediated Fe(III)/Fe(II) redox cycling, which has been observed widely in natural environments. 
We further investigated this phenomenon by studying the effect of disaccharides (maltose, sucrose, lactose) and starch (polysaccharide) on the Fe(III) film formation using the soils collected locally. We found that the three disaccharides all resulted in the Fe(III) films in the soil systems, indicating that the soil microbes were able to use these sugars directly to engage in microbial reduction of soil Fe(III) oxides; yet, the Fe(III) films failed to occur at certain low disaccharide levels. We also found that starch was able to result in the Fe(III) films, but in much less pace and extent. This study indicates that soil microbes are able to use sugars from monosaccharide (glucose) to the disaccharides to polysaccharide (starch) as energy source to engage in microbially mediated redox cycling of Fe(III)/Fe(II). 
",Research Project,Microbially Mediated Redox Cycling of Fe(III)/Fe(II) in Soils:  Effect of Disaccharides and Starch on Formation of Floating Fe(III) Films,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,N/A,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,107
ASC-78,"Cable, Bella (bjcable42)","Cable, Bella (bjcable42);Bacon, Chance (cmbacon42);Williams, Cohen (cwilliams46);Anderson, Emma (eganderson45);Anderson, Fitzgerald (faanderson42);Stengele, Kiri (kastengele42);Yambert, Mary (mcyambert42);Rodgers, Perry (pjrodgers42);Curington, Spencer (sccuringto42);Roberts, Thomas (teroberts44);O'Neal, Alex",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Zhang, Hong","Artificial intelligence (AI) has become increasingly prevalent in research and education. It is well- recognized that AI can provide known information available in overwhelming quantity, speed, and presentation capacity. Yet, the application of AI in handling open-ended questions and reasoning questions and its effectiveness remain to be further explored. Here, we report a study focused on these two critical aspects of the AI application using ChatGPT. This study uses two questions in environmental chemistry: (1) an open-ended question on CO2 sink in global biogeochemical cycle of carbon and (2) a reasoning question on photochemical smog in atmospheric chemistry. These two questions were used to examine the performance, capacity, and accuracy of AI in providing answers to these types of questions. Our study shows that the AI can deliver highly impressive success and competency and possesses significant potential in handling open-ended inquiry questions and reasoning questions such as those we explored. This study joins the efforts to fathom the capacity, potential, and nature of AI.     ",Research Project,A Study on Application of AI in Environmental Chemistry Education and Research,Yes,Human Subjects,Yes,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,This research project is about the applications of AI in handling open-ended questions and reasoning in regard to environmental chemistry. ,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,111
ASC-79,"Cable, Bella (bjcable42)","Cable, Bella (bjcable42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Carroll, William","The analysis of volatile compounds in charcoalified material can give insight into the conditions under which the sample was produced. The degree of aromaticity can be a way to determine the burn temperatures of wildfires that produce charcoalified material. Small molecules are extracted from the sieved sample via a Soxhlet extractor. The Soxhlet extraction effectively brings volatile organic compounds into solution, leaving larger aliphatic molecules behind. Extracted material is characterized by solution-state 13C NMR and mass spectrometry. Degree of aromaticity is measured by the percent of signal present within the aromatic region of the 13C NMR spectra (between 120 and 150 ppm).  Fragmentation patterns characteristic of aromatic molecules in the mass spectrometry data also give insight into aromatic content and show compositional similarities between samples. Samples with known heat treatment temperatures (HTT) will be analyzed, and a calibration curve will be constructed from these results. This will create a model to establish HTT of charcoalified material, providing a tool for understanding wildfire conditions. ",Research Project,Establishing Heat Treatment Temperatures of  Charcoalified Materials by Analysis of Aromaticity,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,112
ASC-80,"Collier, Sarah (smcollier42)","Collier, Sarah (smcollier42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Carroll, William","Developing controlled methods for nanoparticle synthesis is an important step to understanding how different reaction conditions can influence particle formation and morphology. The normal batch synthesis methods tend to produce inconsistent size distribution in particles due to limited control over nucleation and growth conditions. This work investigated a modified flow synthesis method to produce citrate-capped Prussian Blue nanoparticles using iron(III) chloride and potassium ferrocyanide as precursors. In this approach, the first two solutions were combined in a flow system, while sodium citrate was introduced through a separate channel immediately after to influence particle stabilization and growth. The reaction stream exited into a water-filled flask to dilute and effectively stop the reaction. Five runs were conducted to evaluate particle formation and reproducibility under these conditions. Once the five runs were completed, the Prussian blue was baked dry, and the particles were collected to be characterized through scanning electron microscopy (SEM). If successful, this strategy shows potential to improve control over nanoparticle capping and growth compared to traditional methods. ",Research Project,Flow Synthesis of Citrate-Capped Prussian Blue Nanoparticles ,No,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,"Sarah Collier at Tennessee Tech University
William Carroll at Tennessee Tech University",,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,121
ASC-81,"Tetteh, Michael (mttetteh42)","Tetteh, Michael (mttetteh42);Murdock, Justin;Zhang, Hong",Graduate Student | Doctoral,College of Interdisciplinary Studies,Environmental Studies,"Zhang, Hong","Mercury (Hg) contamination remains a persistent environmental and public health concern due to its toxicity, bioaccumulation, and long-range atmospheric transport. This study integrates county-level and species-specific analyses to evaluate long-term patterns of mercury concentrations in freshwater fishes across Tennessee using archived monitoring records from the Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation (TDEC) fish Hg database. We compiled and analyzed four decades (1985-2025) of the publicly available fish mercury monitoring data to assess long-term trends, inter-county variability, shifts in contamination intensity over time, emerging areas of concern and counties demonstrating significant Hg declines.
In parallel, species-level differences were evaluated across taxa, trophic guilds, and feeding strategies to quantify bioaccumulation patterns and biomagnification. Predatory species were compared with omnivores and forage fishes to assess relative mercury burdens and long-term stability of contamination profiles. Statistical approaches, including trellis plots, histograms, and box plots, were used to characterize both geographic and ecological variability without reliance on geospatial mapping.
By linking four decades of monitoring data with species-specific bioaccumulation patterns, this study reveals where mercury risk is greatest – and which fish are most likely to carry it into the human food chain. These findings provide a science-based foundation for targeted environmental monitoring, fishery management strategies and species-specific consumption guidelines.
",Research Project,Long-Term Patterns of Mercury (Hg) Bioaccumulation in Tennessee: County-Level Trends and Species-Specific Dynamics from the Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation Fish Mercury Database ,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,131
ASC-82,"Tetteh, Michael (mttetteh42)","Tetteh, Michael (mttetteh42);Zhan, Xuanzhi;Zhang, Hong",Graduate Student | Doctoral,College of Interdisciplinary Studies,Environmental Studies,"Zhang, Hong","Traditional heavy metal remediation often relies on energy-intensive physical processes or non-selective chemical precipitation. To address these limitations, this research explores a novel biotechnological solution: Recombinant Peptide Fusion (RPF) technology. By genetically engineering microbial hosts to express high-affinity, mercury-binding peptides – such as those derived from metallothioneins or de novo synthetic motifs – we intend to develop a highly selective biosorbent system. These peptides are fused to anchor proteins, allowing for stable expression and increased surface area for mercury sequestration with high binding affinity even in the presence of competing divalent cations. This “designer” approach not only can improve the efficiency of mercury removal from aqueous solutions but also offer a cost-effective and environmentally friendly alternative to conventional remediation. This study is focused on a theoretic framework of the design of the Hg-remediation peptides. Our research demonstrates the potential of synthetic biology to solve persistent environmental challenges through the precision engineering of molecular interfaces.",Research Project,Enhanced Mercury (Hg) Remediation of Freshwater Systems via Recombinant Peptide Fusion Technology,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,132
ASC-83,"Coons, Madelyn (mcoons42)","Coons, Madelyn (mcoons42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Boles, Jeffrey","The illicit drug trade poses significant challenges for law enforcement, necessitating the development of rapid, non-destructive analytical techniques for substance detection. This thesis investigates the application of Raman spectroscopy as a tool for identifying clandestine drugs, particularly when packaged in plastic materials that may obscure spectral signals. Laboratory experiments were conducted using a range of common drugs of abuse, including pseudoephedrine and epinephrine, measured through plastic packaging with different cutting agents that could affect spectral signals. Results indicate that Raman spectroscopy can reliably detect target compounds through thin transparent plastic, with limitations observed in opaque materials. The findings demonstrate the potential for Raman spectroscopy to complement existing forensic tools by providing rapid drug identification, though optimization of spectral preprocessing and instrument sensitivity is required for robust field application. This work contributes to advancing analytical methods in forensic science, with implications for law enforcement and public safety. ",Research Project,Raman Spectroscopy Detection of Clandestine Drugs,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,142
ASC-84,"Hasting, Jacob (jchasting43)","Hasting, Jacob (jchasting43)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Moldenhauer, Jonathan","Electrochemical time of flight (ETOF) is a test that determines the time taken for an electrical current to pass between the gap of two electrodes in a given solution to determine a diffusion coefficient. ETOF is a calibration curve-based method, that has fewer variables in the slope than other electrochemical methods of diffusion coefficient determination.  However, it requires expensive metals and equipment to produce electrode arrays used for ETOF. Using nickel-based spray paint to create the electrodes and then electroplating gold over the top of the layer of paint could produce a more cost-efficient electrode array. After painting multiple electrodes onto a plastic substrate, the electrodes are then plated with 24-karat gold using a solution and electroplater made by Becker Industries. To determine effectiveness, cyclic voltammetry tests are taken in triplicate to compare the gold-plated nickel to bare nickel electrodes. The goal is to determine if these electrodes will perform better than bare nickel electrodes. If successful, an inexpensive electrode could be produced for use in performing ETOF. Our next steps include optimization of the electroplating process and starting proof of concept ETOF to evaluate these electrodes. ",Research Project,Development of Gold-Plated Spray Paint Electrodes for use in Electrochemical Time of Flight,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,Jonathan Moldenhauer,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,147
ASC-85,"Wallace, Aiden (akwallace42)","Wallace, Aiden (akwallace42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Cashman, Derek",The research I have been working on is for how specific compounds bind to and interact with the JNK3 and MKK complexes in a possible treatment for Alzheimer’s disease.  This has been done by using programs such as Alpha Fold and MOE to create 15 compounds and simulate the docking interactions of these compounds with JNK3 and MKK.  I then compared the docking habits of these compounds in 5 different docking models.  These models were created with the use of Alpha Fold.  After this a comparison of what residues where binding occurred was made and the top 3 compounds that had the best binding characteristics were taken and refined further to increase their binding affinity.  The main purpose of this research is to investigate JNK3 receptor inhibition and its application for possible treatment for Alzheimer’s.  Several compounds show promise due to their high affinity binding with JNK3 in a possible use for Alzheimer’s treatment and are being looked into further.  This research is still ongoing and will hopefully bear fruit in addressing the challenges that are associated with the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.,Research Project,JNK3 Inhibition and Possible Alzheimer's Treatment,Yes,No,Yes,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,The use of Alpha Fold was used to make models of JNK3 and MKK that were then used to study the docking habits of compounds.,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,154
ASC-86,"Opoku Acheampong, Clement (copokuach42)","Opoku Acheampong, Clement (copokuach42);Tetteh, Michael (mttetteh42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Zhan, Xuanzhi","Mercury(Hg) contamination in freshwater systems poses a significant environmental challenge due to its toxicity, persistence, and ability to bioaccumulate in aquatic food webs. In Tennessee lakes, monitoring studies have identified mercury concentrations in fish exceeding the advisory threshold of 0.3 mg/kg, raising concerns about ecosystem health and human exposure. This project explores the design of cysteine-rich peptides as a targeted strategy for mercury remediation in contaminated freshwater environments.
The approach leverages the strong chemical affinity between Hg2+ ions and thiol (-SH) groups present in cysteine residues. By designing peptide sequences enriched with cysteine, selective binding sites are created to capture mercury ions from aqueous systems. Additional amino acids are incorporated to enhance solubility, structural stability, and resistance to environmental conditions. Sequence variations are evaluated to understand how composition and structure influence mercury-binding efficiency and selectivity.  To translate this concept into a practical system, the designed peptides will be expressed as fusion proteins and immobilized onto a solid support to form a reusable column for mercury removal. Laboratory experiments will assess binding performance, removal efficiency, and the ability to regenerate the system for repeated use. This strategy aims to provide a scalable and environmentally relevant solution for mercury mitigation.
This presentation highlights progress toward integrating molecular peptide design with environmental remediation strategies to address mercury contamination in Tennessee freshwater systems.
",Research Project,Cysteine-Rich Peptide Design for Targeted Mercury Remediation in Tennessee Lakes,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,162
ASC-87,"Mize, Arly (aamize42)","Mize, Arly (aamize42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Boles, Jeffrey","The Potential use of Red Dye 40 in determining unknown protein concentrations 
The Bradford protein assay is a widely used technique for protein quantification that is based on the binding of a specific dye to protein, leading to a color change measurable at a wavelength of 595 nm. This study tested the efficacy of Red Dye 40 as a substitute for Coomassie Brilliant Blue G-250, the standard dye used in the assay. The Dye was evaluated to see any potential gain Red Dye 40 would have over Coomassie Brilliant Blue G-250. It was selected for their distinct structural and spectral properties in the presence and absence of protein. Proteins such as bovine serum albumin (BSA) and Albumin Human (HSA) serve as test proteins. Red Dye 40’s linearity in standard curves, and sensitivity to protein concentration were analyzed using scanning and single-point UV-Vis spectrophotometry. Results will be presented in this presentation. We hypothesize that it will perform sufficiently and potentially provide more accurate results. The findings will likely highlight the potential for alternative dyes in the Bradford assay since the linear region utilizing Coomassie Brilliant Blue G-250 is often small. Optimization will be necessary for achieving consistency and precision. This study broadens the scope of protein quantification techniques and introduces a potential cost-effective alternative.
",Research Project,The potential use of Red Dye 40 in determining unknown protein concentrations ,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,None,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,171
ASC-88,"Barnes, Anthony","Stengele, Kiri (kastengele42);Davis, Victoria (vldavis42);Barnes, Anthony",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Barnes, Anthony","A dynamic morphology is crucial to neuronal function and plasticity. Shape changes in neuronal cells are very often due to surface receptor activation. The types of receptors involved in this activity vary from growth factor receptors to extra-cellular matrix receptors and G Protein Coupled Receptors (GPCRs). GPR39 is a member of the GPCR family that has been associated with diseases such as depression, epilepsy, stroke, Alzheimer's and addiction. Our preliminary data indicates that it can influence neurite outgrowth in a neuron-like cell line. However, it is currently unclear as to how GPR39 is able to stimulate this response. Our goal is to confirm our preliminary observations while simultaneously characterizing which components of GPR39 intracellular signaling are responsible for the observed shape changes. This will be accomplished using a combination of pharmacologic and genetic manipulations. Our poster will report the results of these studies.",Research Project,Regulation of Neurite Outgrowth by GPR39,No,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,215
ASC-89,"Barnes, Anthony","Raja, Amira (araja42);Brewer, John (jcbrewer45);Barnes, Anthony",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Barnes, Anthony","Multi-protein complexes occur in many cellular contexts and influence various properties of plasma membrane receptors including surface expression, internalization, degradation and signaling. These binding partners have often been found to increase the efficiency and speed of signaling events by acting as scaffolds between signaling molecules. Such interactions are known to shape or regulate the transduction events associated with some G Protein Coupled Receptors (GPCRs).  GPR39 is a member of the GPCR family and has been implicated in a number of neurological and cardiovascular conditions, however the protein interactors for GPR39 remain unknown. Our goal is to identify, validate and characterize the protein interactome for GPR39 using complementary biochemical techniques. This includes proximity biotinylation (also known as BIOID) which allows the in situ labeling of proteins that are very near a protein of interest. This labeling is followed by affinity purification and mass spectrometry-based identification of biotinylated proteins. This work will be combined with mutant forms of GPR39 that will allow us use biochemical methods to map the GPR39 domains required for binding by candidate interactors. We will report the results of these efforts in our poster.",Research Project,Discovery and Mapping of GPR39 Interacting Proteins ,No,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,216
ASC-90,"Barnes, Anthony","Garteiz, Katherine (kggarteiz42);Barnes, Anthony",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Barnes, Anthony","Cellular responses to extracellular signals can result in both short-term changes to cellular pathways or long-term changes in gene expression. These longer-term responses vary by cell type as well as the form and the duration of stimulation. One major family of cell surface receptors linked to altered gene expression are made up of the G Protein Coupled Receptors (GPCRs). Subgroups of GPCRs have been linked to distinct transcriptional responses depending on their intracellular pathways. Few studies have focused on the transcriptional responses that occur following the activation of the GPCR GPR39. This receptor has been linked to multiple conditions of the nervous system including addiction, epilepsy, depression, stroke and Alzheimer's. Our goal is to define the specific transcriptional responses that occur in neural-like cells where GPR39 has been stimulated. This poster will describe our results using multiple time-points following GPR39 stimulation using the well-established agonist TC G1008. Bulk RNAseq will be combined with informatic pathway analysis to map the temporal evolution of gene expression changes in response to receptor activation.",Research Project,Transcriptional profiling of GPR39 stimulation in neural-like cells,No,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,218
ASC-91,"Snyder, Jeffrey (jrsnyder42)","Snyder, Jeffrey (jrsnyder42);Cashman, Derek",Undergraduate Student,College of Engineering,Chemical Engineering,"Cashman, Derek","This study focuses on computational explorations into methylxanthines, including caffeine, theobromine, and theophylline, in combination with interactions of the adenosine receptor by combining molecular docking with ab initio quantum mechanical analysis. Regarding ligand recognition, minor consideration was given to the consensus amino acid sequence of adenosine receptors and their relationship to potential binding sites. Using MOE 2024 and Gaussian 16, each ligand was docked into the receptor active site, generating five low-energy conformations ranked by binding Gibbs free energy (ΔG, kcal/mol). Quantum mechanical calculations were performed using G16 at the B3LYP/6-31G level of theory to evaluate electronic structure and density functional theory. The HOMO and LUMO orbitals were calculated to identify regions of electron donation and acceptance. Pharmacophore models were derived from docking to assess orbital distribution and binding interactions. Noncovalent contributions to ligand receptor stability (London dispersion forces and electrostatic interactions) were defined by Coulomb’s law and analyzed. This study aims to demonstrate the correlation between electronic structure, ligand binding behavior, and differences among methylxanthines and their influence on receptor affinity. The results will include five docked confirmations, ligand interaction maps, HOMO and LUMO maps, quantum mechanical calculations, and various insights into receptor affinity.",Research Project,"Molecular Docking, Pharmacophore Modeling, and Quantum Mechanical Analysis of Methylxanthine Binding to the Adenosine Receptor",Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,220
ASC-92,"Kirby, Cayden (ckkirby42)","Kirby, Cayden (ckkirby42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Zhan, Xuanzhi","The c-Jun N-terminal kinase (JNK) signaling pathway is a critical component of the mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) network, activated in response to environmental stress, inflammatory cytokines, and growth factors. Among the isoforms produced from JNK1, JNK2, and JNK3, the JNK3 isoform is of particular interest due to its restricted expression in the central nervous system, heart, and testes, and its strong association with neurodegenerative diseases. Dysregulated JNK3 activation contributes to neuronal dysfunction and apoptosis in conditions such as Alzheimer’s disease, Parkinson’s disease, and ischemic stroke. However, the high sequence homology among JNK isoforms limits the specificity of traditional kinase inhibitors, increasing off-target effects. Recent studies have identified the NJ38 peptide, derived from an ASK1-interacting region of JNK3, as a potential isoform-selective inhibitor. NJ38 preferentially binds JNK3 and disrupts interactions with upstream kinases, enabling selective inhibition without significantly affecting JNK1 or JNK2. The objective of this study was to evaluate the specificity, efficacy, and cellular activity of NJ38 using reconstructed protein systems and mammalian cell-based assays. JNK isoforms and peptide constructs were expressed in HEK293T and SH-SY5Y cells, and JNK3 activation was induced using UV irradiation, oxidative stress, and chemical stress. Western blot analysis was performed to assess JNK phosphorylation and determine the effect of NJ38 expression on pathway activation. The findings support NJ38 as a promising candidate for isoform-specific JNK3 inhibition and highlight the therapeutic potential of targeting protein–protein interactions in MAPK signaling.",Research Project,Evaluating the Activation of c-Jun N-Terminal Kinases in Mammalian Cells,No,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,224
ASC-93,"Reichter, Clara (cgreichter42)","Reichter, Clara (cgreichter42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Zhan, Xuanzhi","c-Jun N-terminal Kinase 3, a neuron-specific isoform of JNKs, controls essential neuronal cell physiological functions, including development, differentiation, regeneration, and apoptosis. JNK3 contains a unique N-terminus, named NJ38 here, compared to the ubiquitously expressed JNK1 and 2. Very minimal information is known about the structure or function of this sequence, but it has the potential to mediate JNK3-specific interactions, as it is not found in the other two JNK isoforms. A systematic strategy is proposed here to identify the potential binding partners of this motif by biotin identification (BioID), a protein-proximity labeling approach. The NJ38 was fused to the “promiscuous” biotin ligase (Turbo). The fusion protein biotinylates proximal proteins. The biotinylated proteins will be further identified by mass-spectrometry and Western-blot analyses. There are no current JNK3 inhibitors that are either FDA-approved or being produced, but research around JNK3, especially on the extended N-terminus region, identifies it as a strong, attractive target to exploit novel binding partners as potential drug pathways. ",Research Project,"Identification of Novel Binding Partners of NJ38, a Unique N-terminal Motif of JNK3 by BioID",Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,"Dr. Paul Barnes, TN Tech University, College of Arts and Sciences",,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,229
ASC-94,"Barnes, Anthony","Stovall, Caleb (clstovall43);Ludwig, Sophia (sludwig42);Barnes, Anthony",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Barnes, Anthony","Cells use a number of mechanisms to sense their environment including a family of cell surface receptors known as G Protein Coupled Receptors (GPCRs). This is a large family of proteins (~800 members) that are used to detect a variety of stimuli that range from light and scents to ions and neurotransmitters. While they share a common seven-transmembrane architecture, the intracellular signaling pathways to which they couple can vary dramatically. Despite this variety, one near-universal consequence of GPCR activation is the phosphorylation of the protein kinase ERK. This is a central enzyme in intracellular signaling and also serves as a convenient readout of receptor activation. Interestingly, the time-course of Erk activation can be distinct for different GPCRs as well as different receptor activators (also known as ligands) at the same receptor. One GPCR that has been reported to have multiple agonists is known as GPR39. This receptor has also been reported to contribute to a number of pathologic states in different organ systems. Our goal is to characterize the kinetics of GPR39 activation and inactivation using a combination of biochemistry and pharmacology to better understand the impact of receptor activation by various ligands and how this may affect downstream signaling kinetics, ultimately informing GPR39's value as a therapeutic target.",Research Project,GPR39 Signal Transduction Dynamics in a Neuron-like Cell Model,No,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,230
ASC-95,"Hardy, Christopher (cjhardy42)","Hardy, Christopher (cjhardy42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Boles, Jeffrey","     The accuracy of artificial intelligence protein structural prediction models often relies on the evaluation of genetic context found within the intra- and inter-sequence relationships of multiple sequence alignment (MSA) files. However, depending on a protein’s family and the relevance of its constituent domains, sequence databases may produce sparse results for an MSA query. Additionally, the complex deep learning architectures used to interpret MSA files can obscure the exact nature of internal amino acid relationships resulting in a black box. Instead of forgoing MSA-based models, we propose a machine-learning based data pipeline for the refinement and human-interpretable evaluation of MSAs generated by two popular protein structural prediction models, AlphaFold and RoseTTAFold. For contrast, we compared our approach to workflows utilizing the MSA-free models OmegaFold and ESMFold. Within the pipeline, each sequence within an MSA is organized into overlapping contiguous fragments (termed Kmers) that are arranged according to a predetermined set of physicochemical values. Then, standard vector similarity and statistical metrics are used to evaluate various intra and inter-sequence relationships in a human-interpretable manner. Current results suggest that this novel pipeline is useful for both evaluating the quality of MSAs and for exploring the energetic and conformational spaces of various proteins. While the accuracy of the individual protein predictions was often similar between all four tested models, the inclusion of an MSA within AlphaFold’s and RoseTTAFold’s inference processes provides researchers an opportunity that overshadows the potential downfalls that models like OmegaFold and ESMFold are attempting to circumvent. ",Research Project,Physicochemical Kmer Encoding for the Enhanced Evaluation and Expansion of Artificial Intelligence Protein Structural Prediction Models,Yes,No,Yes,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,"The project involves the use of various AI models for the prediction of protein structures. Additionally, some AI methods are used within the evaluation of the resulting predicted structures. ",,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,231
ASC-96,"Pruett, Hannah (hgpruett42)","Pruett, Hannah (hgpruett42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Boles, Jeffrey","The utilization of selenomethionine (SeMet) as a phasing tool coupled with multi-wavelength anomalous diffraction has yielded the solution of a multitude of three-dimensional structures. Studies on structural stability have typically been carried out via kinetic analysis under varying conditions. These results are then compared to those of the wild-type protein. Some purified recombinant selenoproteins have been proven to have reduced activity and/or altered three-dimensional structures. This project involves furthering the understanding of protein stability when proteins contain bio-incorporated unnatural amino acids through the investigation of the secondary structure stability of DHFR in the presence of bound methotrexate. This goal will be achieved through the comparison of wild-type and selenomethionyl-DHFR secondary structures at varying pH and temperature via Circular Dichroism (CD) spectra. The varying pH and temperature will induce unfolding or refolding of the respective protein. CD signals between 190 and 250 nm will be collected and used to determine changes in helical, sheet, and random coil content. ",Research Project,Purification of Wild Type and Selenomethionine DHFR and Analysis by Circular Dichroism,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,240
ASC-97,"Khodyakov, Vasiliy (vzhukova42)","Khodyakov, Vasiliy (vzhukova42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Cashman, Derek","The Virtual Reality (VR) software Nanome is a Computer Aided Drug Discovery (CADD) program developed for real-time collaboration in molecular biology and chemistry. Currently the software is primarily used in the pharmaceutical industry, but not much has been explored for the educational potential of the software. This project aims at explaining and explaining how this software can be utilized as an educational tool for higher education as well as a research tool for universities. There are currently two different versions of Nanome, V1 which is an all round software and V2 which is actively in development an currently focuses more on protein modelling and analysis. The two versions were analyzed with a focus on their general strengths; version 1 was analyzed using two reactions: the Diels-Alder reaction and a cycloaddition reaction, version 2 was analyzed utilizing Cytochrome C in sequence alignment between equine and tuna variants, as well as  structure determination with comparison to results calculated using AlphaFold. The results of this research found that the software can cover a wide range of chemistry disciplines in both education and educational research, and the results of it will be presented along with the data found",Research Project,Exploration of Virtual Reality Chemistry in Higher Education,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,253
ASC-98,"Decatur, Sydney (sdecatur42)","Decatur, Sydney (sdecatur42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Callender, Andrew",,Research Project,Scents and Sensitivity:  Benzaldehyde in Candles With ASAP MS Using a Surrogate Internal Standard ,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,266
ASC-99,"Houston, Rachel (rchouston42)","Houston, Rachel (rchouston42);Rodgers, William (wkrodgers42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Cojocaru, Oana",,Research Project,Theophylline as a cation and anion precursor for ionic liquids,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,267
ASC-100,"Uduehi, Gloria (geuduehi42)","Uduehi, Gloria (geuduehi42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Cojocaru, Oana","Albuterol is widely prescribed for the management of asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Despite its effectiveness, conventional administration by inhalation or oral routes presents challenges, including poor patient compliance (it requires frequent dosing), short duration of action, and variability in bioavailability due to first-pass metabolism. To address these limitations, novel strategies are needed to improve therapeutic delivery. One promising approach is the transformation of albuterol into ionic liquid (IL) formulations by pairing its cationic moiety with pharmaceutically acceptable organic anions. Such ionic liquids can disrupt the crystalline solid state of albuterol, yielding a liquid form with enhanced solubility, tunable hydrophilicity/lipophilicity balance, and favorable physicochemical properties for skin permeation. By tailoring the choice of counterions, IL formulations can be engineered to optimize stability, permeability, and drug release kinetics for transdermal administration. This strategy not only has the potential to extend the duration of action and reduce dosing frequency, but also to provide a non-invasive alternative to inhalation, particularly beneficial for pediatric and geriatric patients who face difficulties with inhaler use. This presentation highlights the synthesis of albuterol-derived ionic liquids, with a focus on spectroscopic and thermal analyses used to verify their formation and assess their potential as liquid-state drug formulations.",Research Project,Spectroscopic and thermal insights into liquid state albuterol compounds,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,270
ASC-101,"Nortey, Patience (pmnortey42)","Nortey, Patience (pmnortey42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Cojocaru, Oana",,Research Project,Spectroscopic characterization of liquid-state Parkinson drugs,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,271
ASC-102,"Land, Olivia (orland42)","Land, Olivia (orland42);Spangler, Riley (rgspangler42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Cojocaru, Oana",,Research Project,Assessing Thermal Characteristics of Trifluoperazine Liquid-State Ionic Formulations,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,"Olivia Land Tennessee Tech University
Riley Spangler Tennessee Tech University
O. Andreea Cojocaru Tennessee Tech University",,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,272
ASC-103,"Kaiser, Robert (rmkaiser42)","Kaiser, Robert (rmkaiser42);Robertson, Thomas (throbertso42);Cojocaru, Oana",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Cojocaru, Oana",,Research Project,Thermal Profiling of Quinine- and Quinidine- Derived  Double Salt Ionic Liquids with NALC,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,275
ASC-104,"Svaighert, Jonathan (jsvaigher42)","Svaighert, Jonathan (jsvaigher42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Biology,"Cojocaru, Oana",,Research Project,Extraction of chitin from cicada exoskeletons collected during the 2024 and 2025 emergences in Tennessee,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,277
ASC-105,"Thilakarathne, Lakshi (lmthilakar42)",Lakshi Thilakarathne - EVS PhD - Chemistry Members,Graduate Student | Doctoral,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Carrick, Jesse",,Research Project,Evaluation of Pyridinyl Soft-Lewis Basic Complexants for Minor Actinide Separation from Simulated Spent Nuclear Fuel,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,Prof. Dale Ensor,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,279
ASC-106,"Thilakarathne, Lakshi (lmthilakar42)","Thilakarathne, Lakshi (lmthilakar42)",Graduate Student | Doctoral,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Carrick, Jesse","Evaluation of Pyridinyl Soft-Lewis Basic Complexants for Minor Actinide Separation from Simulated Spent Nuclear Fuel
Lakshi Thilakarathne, Dale Ensor, Jesse D. Carrick
Department of Chemistry, Tennessee Technological University, Cookeville, TN 38505-0001, USA

Long-term sustainability of nuclear energy depends on the effective management of spent nuclear fuel (SNF), particularly the selective separation of trivalent minor actinides (An³⁺) from chemically similar lanthanides (Ln³⁺). Achieving this separation is essential for reducing long-term radiotoxicity and enabling closure of the nuclear fuel cycle. This research focuses on the rational design, synthesis, and evaluation of soft-Lewis basic nitrogen-donor complexants for the selective An separation using both liquid–liquid extraction (SANEX-type) and solid-phase systems. Established pyridine, bipyridine, and phenanthroline-based bis-1,2,4-triazinyl frameworks provide a foundation for developing advanced complexant architectures with improved stability and separation performance under acidic conditions. To address limitations associated with conventional solvent-based processes, this work also investigates solvent-impregnated resins (SIRs) as more sustainable and scalable separation platforms. In parallel, new ligand scaffolds incorporating 1,2-pyridazine units are being explored as next-generation design strategies to enhance coordination control and process adaptability. Together, these efforts aim to advance efficient and environmentally compatible technologies for sustainable nuclear fuel cycle management. Design, synthesis, and evaluation of advanced soft-Lewis basic complexants across liquid–liquid and solid-phase separation platforms will be presented.

",Research Project,Evaluation of Pyridinyl Soft-Lewis Basic Complexants for Minor Actinide Separation from Simulated Spent Nuclear Fuel,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,Prof Dale Ensor,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,280
ASC-107,"Gnyawali, Krishna","Gnyawali, Krishna",Graduate Student | Doctoral,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Carrick, Jesse","The selective separation of trivalent actinides (An³⁺) from chemically similar lanthanides (Ln³⁺) remains a major challenge in advanced nuclear waste management. Since the introduction of bis-1,2,4-triazinyl-2,6-pyridine (BTP) complexants by Kolarik in 1999, the development of an optimized complexant for actinide-lanthanide separation has been an ongoing pursuit.  Here, we report a streamlined synthesis of a TODGA-inspired, amide-functionalized bis-1,2,4-triazinyl-2,6-pyridine (BTP) complexant via an efficient alkylation–condensation approach. Introduction of amide groups enhances solubility in industrially relevant diluents (Exxal-8, 1-octanol, toluene) and improves extraction performance. The complexant exhibits high distribution values, fast equilibration (~30 min), and excellent selectivity for ²⁴¹Am³⁺ over ¹⁵²–¹⁵⁴Eu³⁺ under simulated spent fuel conditions. Back-extraction studies demonstrate efficient actinide recovery and good recyclability of the complexant. This presentation will highlight key aspects of complexant design scheme, synthetic preparation, equilibrium study, acid and complexant concentrations study, as well as decomplexation, underscoring the potential of this novel complexant for advanced nuclear waste management strategies.",Research Project,Exploration of TODGA-inspired complexant for minor actinide extraction,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,"I am currently working as a postdoctoral researcher and am interested in presenting my research, if the opportunity is open to participants beyond undergraduate and graduate students.",,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,286
ASC-108,"Djenini, Noel (ncdjenini42)","Djenini, Noel (ncdjenini42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Cojocaru, Oana","Phenytoin (5,5-diphenylhydantoin) is a well-established antiepileptic medication commonly prescribed for the management of generalized tonic-clonic and partial seizures, which are among the most frequent manifestations of epilepsy. As a hydantoin derivative, phenytoin is typically administered orally or intravenously. Orally, it exerts its therapeutic effect primarily through sodium channel inhibition, stabilizing abnormal neuronal activity; however, intravenous administration carries risks such as cardiovascular complications when delivered too rapidly. Furthermore, clinical use is limited by poor water solubility and susceptibility to polymorphic transitions, which complicate dose optimization and result in unpredictable plasma concentrations. To address these limitations, transdermal delivery is proposed as an alternative to oral or injectable administration. This route bypasses first-pass hepatic metabolism and reduces interpatient variability in drug absorption. The approach involves converting phenytoin into dual-active pharmaceutical ingredient-based ionic liquids (API-ILs), salts with melting points below body temperature formed by pairing the phenytoin ion with pharmaceutically active counterions. This strategy enhances solubility, membrane permeability, and bioavailability while improving thermal stability, thereby reducing the need for frequent therapeutic monitoring. This presentation highlights the synthesis and characterization of dual-active liquid-state phenytoin derivatives via metathesis reactions, where the phenytoin ion is paired with selected bioactive counterions. The resulting ionic liquids are evaluated using spectroscopic and thermal analyses to confirm their structural and physicochemical properties. Ultimately, this approach aims to improve epilepsy treatment by providing a more reliable, stable, and patient-friendly phenytoin formulation through transdermal delivery.",Research Project,Liquid-State Phenytoin Formulations for Improved Epilepsy Therapy.,No,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,289
ASC-109,"Yambert, Mary (mcyambert42)","Yambert, Mary (mcyambert42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Cojocaru, Oana",,Research Project,Thermal characterization of aliphatic phenothiazine based double salt ionic liquids,No,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,291
ASC-110,"Wasserman, Hannah (hmwasserma42)","Wasserman, Hannah (hmwasserma42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Carroll, William",,Research Project,Synthesis and potential use of silver nanoparticles,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,292
ASC-111,"Penn, Zoe (zmpenn42)","Penn, Zoe (zmpenn42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Murphy, Kyle",,Research Project,Depolymerization of PET-Based Microplastics With Green Chemistry Conditions ,,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,Kyle Murphy ,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,294
ASC-112,"Wood, Shayla (sgwood42)","Wood, Shayla (sgwood42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Carrick, Jesse","The nuclear fuel cycle provides substantial benefits for energy production; however, several challenges must be addressed before a fully closed fuel cycle can be realized. One of the primary obstacles is the accumulation of spent nuclear fuel, which contains significant quantities of radioactive actinides and lanthanides. These elements contribute heavily to the long-term radiotoxicity of nuclear waste, making storage both environmentally and economically problematic. As a result, considerable research has focused on developing methods to separate actinides from lanthanides, thereby reducing overall radiotoxicity and enabling the potential recycling of these elements back into the nuclear fuel cycle. One promising strategy for achieving this separation involves the use of soft-Lewis basic complexants that preferentially bind actinides over lanthanides. This selectivity arises from fundamental differences in chemical behavior: actinides exhibit greater soft acid character, whereas lanthanides are typically classified as hard acids. A variety of complexants have been developed and shown to effectively discriminate between these two classes of elements. However, further structural optimization and functionalization of these complexants are necessary to improve their performance and enable practical industrial application. This work focuses on modifying existing complexant frameworks through the conversion of amide functionalities to amines via the Hofmann rearrangement. The objective is to transform known scaffolds containing amide substituents into their corresponding amine derivatives. Following synthesis, these modified substrates will be evaluated for solubility, stability, and separation efficiency. This specific presentation will discuss current optimized conditions, potential substrate scope, spectroscopic data, and future directions. ",Research Project,Progress Towards the Hofmann Rearrangement of Heteroaryl Carboxamides to Afford Heteroaryl Amino Complexant Synthons ,Yes,No,No,Chemistry,ASC - Chemistry,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,295
ASC-113,"Amaya, Daniela (damaya42)","Amaya, Daniela (damaya42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Johnson, Kristen","The oxidation of hydrocarbon thin films plays an important role in material stability, indoor air chemistry, and lubricant degradation. However, oxidation processes involving gas-surface interfaces remain less understood than bulk liquid systems. This research investigates the changes in oxidation rates in hydrocarbon thin films and examines the heterogeneous reactions between organic thin films, composed of long-chain alkenes (C15-C18) with one carbon-carbon double bond, and ozone. Thin films are deposited onto an attenuated total reflectance (ATR) crystal and then exposed to ozone generated in a controlled flow system. Attenuated Total Reflectance Fourier Transform Infrared (FTIR-ATR) spectroscopy is used to monitor the chemical changes within the films during oxidation. Changes in the infrared spectral peaks are monitored to track the formation of oxygen-containing functional groups and to quantify the reaction process. Spectral analysis and peak-fitting methods are used to determine the oxidation rates from the FTIR data. Additional analysis may include the characterization of chemical changes occurring within the oxidized films using mass spectrometry or atomic force microscopy (AFM). If successful, this research could improve the understanding of oxidation processes occurring at gas-film interfaces and could contribute to improved models of hydrocarbon film degradation. A greater understanding of heterogeneous oxidation reactions could help explain the aging and stability of hydrocarbon materials. It can also support predictions of lubricant lifetime and indoor chemical processes.",Research Project,Oxidation Rate Changes in Organic Thin Films using FTIR-ATR Spectroscopy,Yes,No,No,Dean of Arts and Science Office,ASC - Dean of Arts and Science Office,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,119
ASC-114,"Lamantia, Anthony (amlamantia42)","Lamantia, Anthony (amlamantia42);Racek, Gillian (gmracek42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Earth Sciences,"Luna, Jeannette","Understanding surface features at the Lunar South Pole (LSP) is essential for deciphering the Moon's geological history and supporting future Artemis exploration missions. This study analyzes an established database of over 90,000 individual boulders and 750 boulder fields mapped across more than 9,870 km² of the LSP. We also utilized high-resolution imagery derived from the Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter (LRO) Narrow Angle Camera (NAC) mosaics and Lunar Orbiter Laser Altimeter (LOLA) digital elevation models (DEMs).

This research tests the hypothesis that boulder placement is not random but significantly correlated with specific geomorphic features, such as scarps, depressions, and craters, and specific slope thresholds. Here, we aim to refine the current classification system of the boulder database to be more specific to the boulder’s potentially correlated parent feature. Using ArcGIS Pro, we performed spatial density analyses and statistical correlations between boulder locations and slope gradients derived from LOLA DEMs. 

Preliminary results aim to identify ""slope thresholds"" for boulder stability and provide quantitative assessments of rockfall potential. We can differentiate between boulders currently in situ and those displaced by seismic or impact events by mapping boulder tracks as linear features and generating slope-frequency histograms. This work refines the existing LSP database, offering a critical framework for hazard analysis and landing site selection by identifying stable versus unstable terrain. Ultimately, these findings contribute to a deeper understanding of lunar surface evolution and provide an important step towards remote analysis of surface features for human exploration.
",Research Project,Lunar South Pole Boulders: An Analysis of Distributions and Geomorphology,Yes,No,No,Dean of Arts and Science Office,ASC - Dean of Arts and Science Office,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,148
ASC-115,"Racek, Gillian (gmracek42)","Racek, Gillian (gmracek42);Baughman, Emma (ebaughman42);Lamantia, Anthony (amlamantia42);Luna, Jeannette",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Earth Sciences,"Luna, Jeannette","Permanently shadowed regions (PSRs) at the lunar south pole experience little to no direct solar radiation, creating environmental conditions that differ significantly from nearby illuminated terrain. These conditions may influence the size, preservation, and spatial distribution of surface boulders, rock fragments that measure greater than 1-2 meters. This study investigates boulder distribution and potential origin within Shackleton Crater using high-resolution imagery from ShadowCam and geospatial analysis in ArcGIS. The working hypothesis is that reduced solar radiation in permanently shadowed regions leads to decreased thermal weathering, allowing larger boulders to persist compared to those found in illuminated areas.
	Boulders within the study were systematically mapped using several feature types to characterize their occurrence and morphology. Individual boulders were digitized as point features, clusters of boulders were mapped using polygon features, and visible boulder tracks were recorded using line features to identify potential movement pathways. In addition, unusually large boulders were outlined as polygons to distinguish them from the general population. Preliminary mapping has identified 4,762 individual boulders, 9 boulder clusters, and 24 significant boulders within the Shackleton Crater region. The largest observed boulder measures approximately 70 meters in length, which is significantly larger than typical boulders documented in nearby illuminated terrain.
	Preliminary observation suggest that permanently shadowed regions may preserve larger, and potentially older boulders due to reduced solar-driven weathering processes. Continued analysis will examine spatial patterns, cluster formation, and possible source regions to better understand the processes controlling boulder distribution in permanently shadowed environments. 
",Research Project,"Boulder Distribution and Preservation in Permanently Shadowed Regions of Shackleton Crater, Lunar South Pole",Yes,No,No,Dean of Arts and Science Office,ASC - Dean of Arts and Science Office,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,149
ASC-116,"Uselton, Drew (duselton42)","Uselton, Drew (duselton42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Earth Sciences,"Luna, Jeannette","SP Crater, located 40 km north of Flagstaff, Arizona, is a volcano with a geologically recent, yet contested eruption. The proposed eruption ages range from 70 ka to 5.5 ka based on OSL and radiometric U-Th dating of porphyritic basalts. However, the underlying sedimentary rocks may record a more precise estimate of SP Crater’s eruption. The underlying Permian sedimentary unit, the Coconino Sandstone, was sampled for radiometric dating using zircons. This process measures the decay of U-Th through time and the release of built up He gas from heating the crystal. The age thus records the last time the zircon passed through the 180 – 200° C closure temperature. The new method yielded an age that neither matches previous eruptive ages, nor the age of the Coconino sandstone (275 – 260 Ma). Instead, the He gases released from the zircon crystals recorded an age around 110 – 70 Ma. We interpret this result to indicate that the sample was part of the sandstone and was buried to a depth of over 6 km to reach the 180 – 200 ° C and to release He gas. This data suggests a geologic history where: (1) the Coconino Sandstone was deposited around ~275-260 Ma; (2) the unit was buried to a depth of 6km around 110-70 Ma; (3) the unit was exhumed to the surface over the last 70 Ma; and (4) the SP Crater volcano erupted. Moreover, the unit cannot be reliably used to test the age of the SP eruption.",Research Project,"Using Radiometric Dating to Determine Burial History in a Sedimentary Basin, San Franscisco Volcanic Field, Arizona",No,No,No,Dean of Arts and Science Office,ASC - Dean of Arts and Science Office,,,,,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,157
ASC-117,"Robertson, Angelina (aarobertso42)","Robertson, Angelina (aarobertso42)",Undergraduate Student,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Johnson, Kristen","Oxidation is one of the main factors when it comes to quality degradation of materials. It is a natural process of a chemical or substance chemically combining with oxygen. When a substance or chemical goes through the process of being oxidized it creates a new product with separate characteristics and properties from the original substance. The issue of oxidation primarily affects the automotive industry by affecting the performance of paraffinic lubricants, which consist of both branched and straight chain alkenes and are primarily in liquid phase. However, research for the gas phase interface through oxidation is a less researched topic, even though the interface is more relevant in indoor environments where lubricated mechanisms are exposed to air. This research will study the kinetics of 1-Hexadecene through oxidation, an alpha-olein that is primarily in automotive lubricants, by ozone and hydroxyl radicals. In order to examine the kinetics of 1-Hexadecene, this research will use the two methods of gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS) and attenuated total reflectance Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (ATR-FTIR). With the use of these methods, the hypothesis is that the kinetics of 1-Hexadecene will not be homogeneous across the film and that there will be small deposits of high-density deposits that will then lead to further insight of the aging process of the paraffin lubricant films. The outcomes of the research will contribute to understanding the oxidation mechanisms at the gas-lubricant interface, improve existing models of lubricant aging, and aid in the development of hydrocarbon-based products.",Research Project,Measuring Oxidation Kinetics of 1-Hexadecene in Gas Phase,Yes,No,No,Dean of Arts and Science Office,ASC - Dean of Arts and Science Office,,,,Dr. Johnson Kristen of Tennessee Technological College.,,,ASC,College of Arts and Science,,,2026,242
ASC-118,"Ebinum, Emmanuella (eebinum42)","Ebinum, Emmanuella (eebinum42)",Graduate Student | Master's,College of Arts and Sciences,Chemistry,"Johnson, Kristen","This study investigates the impact of molecular self-assembly on the reactions of cooking emissions with gas-phase compounds, oxidants, and chlorine species from cleaning products. With approximately 80% of our time spent indoors, understanding how these factors affect indoor air quality is crucial. Cooking emissions introduce unsaturated fatty acids like oleic acid, which can deposit on surfaces and undergo three-dimensional (3D) self-assembly, forming ordered structures such as lipid bilayers and micelles. These organized films significantly influence their heterogeneous reactivity.

When oleic acid molecules form ordered structures, their reactive double bonds become shielded, making them less accessible to oxidants. To explore this phenomenon, we coated an attenuated total reflectance (ATR) crystal with a 1:1 mixture of oleic acid and its salt, sodium oleate, and exposed it to gas-phase reactants like ozone (O3) and hypochlorous acid (HOCl) under controlled conditions. We monitored chemical cha